title: For Trade:  U.S. Training Rifle Co. 1903 Springfield. WWI
postcontent:
I have for trade a WWI training rifle. It was made by the U.S. Training Rifle Company for training during the WWI years to our troops, cadets, academies ect..

It is in pretty good shape condidering what they were put through. It has a black walnut finger groove stock, and all the other parts are made out of metal. Bolt functions just like a 1903. Has the same weight, length, and feel of a 1903 springfield. There were made this way to copy it in feel and look so the soldier would be familiar with it. Bolt action works like a rear 1903 and firing pin inside bolt cocks and releases when trigger pulled. 

http://user.pa.net/~the.macs/USTR.html  here is a link to info on this rare training rifle. The most common found training rifles found today are the WWII era Parris Dunn rifles which are not as detailed and authentic to the original 1903 as these were. 

This one does not have a rear sight leaf and looks to never have had one nor a front sight and no rear sling swivel. In overall good shape and a lot of history behind it also. 

You can call or text me anytime up till midnight.  REDACTED.

title: For Sale:  OPEN BOLT 1981 RPB SAP M10 9mm Mac 10 ingram
postcontent:
This is the REAL DEAL!! A Ultra-Rare! 1981 mfg, RPB Industries sapM10 "open bolt" in 9mm cal. Comes with (2) 32rnd factory steel mags. These were banned by ATF and can absolutely never be made again, but the select few stamped SAPM10 (semi automatic pistol) were grandfathered in and considered exempt from this ruling.it has been said that there are less than 400 of these still in existence, most were picked up by class 3 dealers and converted to fully automatic weapons. This could be the last chance to legally own one of classic weapons! You may not need it today, but you may be glad you have it tomorrow! RPB (which has been rumored to stand for Rape, Pillage, and Burn... but actually stands for the initials of the company founders) manufactured the only semi auto open bolt variety of the M10 ever made, most were stamped "sM10" but a very few were made with the model stamped as "sapM10" (an abbreviation for semi auto pistol) These few are the only open bolt M10's which are not banned as assault weapons by the state of CA. This is a very rare variant of an extremely hard to come by pistol. In 1979, Wayne Daniel manufactured a semi auto only version and somehow (miraculously, I still don't know how he pulled it off) was able to get the BATFE to approve it as a Title 1 firearm i.e. a 'Regular' gun. The open bolt semi auto M10 pistol manufactured by RPB were initially made using surplus SMG parts bought from Military Armaments Corporation when they went out of buisness in 1978. The period of manufacture was short lived however as in 1982 - the BATFE reversed its decision on approving the open bolt semi auto guns when it was found that they were easily converted to full auto. Effective June 21st 1982, any new M10's made as open bolt pistols were to be considered Title 2 firearms (i.e. machine guns).... These were produced for less than 3 years and can never be made again. In case you don't believe that there is any way this can be legal please read the text of the ATF decision rule 82-2 which banned any more of these from being made but allowed the ones already in circulation to be grandfathered. This is sold as a unique collectible pistol, you are responsible for complying with all state and federal laws (i.e. don't do anything illegal with it, to it, around it. Don't think illegal thoughts, don't contemplate any hypothetical, don't ask any STUPID questions, and don't discuss anything nefarious even as a joke...)





$1750

Really looking for trades, FN 5.7,  High end .357 mags, remington 700 in .308, semit auto shotguns, compact 1911s, etc. What do you have? Message me through here or text me at 615-900-6734. Pics available on request.

title: For Sale/Trade:  Ammo - .223/5.56, 7.62x39, 7.62x54R, .45 ACP, 9mm, 30-30, 30 Carbine + More!
location: Albany to Saratoga, Albany, New York
postcontent:
Ammo for sale, I came into some cash and decided to invest it. I thought long and hard about purchasing precious metals and finally came upon the realization that the only metal worth the investment in these turbulent times is brass. I bought up some cheap stocks of ammo some for me, some for friends and some to resell. So without further ado, here's what I got or what I can get.

*.223/5.56 NATO    - $0.65 to $0.56/round
.308/7.62 NATO    - $0.90 to $0.78/round
*7.62x39    - $0.45 to $0.32/round
*7.62x54R    - $0.40 to $0.27/round
*9mm    - $0.48 to $0.41/round
*.45 ACP    - $0.64 to $0.53/round
45 LC    - $1.00 to $0.83/round
*30-30    - $0.90 to $0.78/round
*30 Carbine    - $0.58 to $0.52/round
30-06    - $0.90 to $0.78/round
8mm Mauser    - $0.40 to $0.34/round

*indicates ammunition available immediately, others can be ordered and will arrive in a week or so.

All ammo is cheap stuff, either steel casings or mil-surplus, most is non-corrosive (I think the 30-06 and 7.62x54R is the only corrosive ammo, oh maybe the 8mm's too). If you have any requests for another caliber I don't have or would like 'more premium' ammunition feel free to make a request, I have access to all sorts of stuff, though I don't have much of a discount.

I'm aware pricing is not ideal, however it is in stock, and I can get much, much more (unlike most retailers these days). I'm only trying to make a few extra bucks so I can continue to invest in brass, and continue to supply our citizens with ammo. I'm using the profits to start up an alternative news website for my own personal investigative journalistic activities for the upstate NY region. So the slightly inflated pricing is funding a local movement for truth... if you're into that kinda thing..... or gave the slightest bit of a f'ck to read my long winded message.
